<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-CEG-overall" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>CEG Overall</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>This chapter covers the overall structure and relationships of a major triad. The notes C, E, and G which make up a C Major Triad are used as an example. Using the same shape but starting from a different Root note, produces the major chord related to that Root note. Thus knowing the triad shape given in this diagram means that you can gernerate any other major triad by using the same shape.
      Similarly a mirror image of this shape on the free bass keyboard produces a major triad. See next section 5.2.
    </p>
  </introduction>
